<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-961-624  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 961 624.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 28 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Project Notify promises communication in a disaster.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woods, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Project NotifyTelecommunicationsDisaster PlanningDisaster Management.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>PROJECT NOTIFY PROMISES COMMUNICATION IN A DISASTER INCLINE VILLAGE, NEVADA,U.S.A., 1989 NOV 24 (NB) -- The best method of communication during theOctober 17 San Francisco earthquake and the earlier Hurricane Hugo was hamradio or computer bulletin board operators who served as low-priority messagetraffickers while regular phone lines were jammed or inoperational.andP;  A newnon-profit group has been set up to serve that need on a minute's notice.andM;Project Notify, a Nevada non-profit corporation, has been formed to encouragethe use of information science, communication technology, and personalcomputers to provide alternative paths for private communications into andout of areas affected by disasters.andP;  A network of Project Notify volunteersis being sought to respond to crisis as the &quot;Red Cross&quot; oftelecommunications.andP;  Volunteers need battery-powered laptops, and will amassand send messages to the service's central database in Nevada.andP;  The messagesare then picked up by the regional volunteer who will implement the requests-- a notification to loved ones that all is fine, for instance.andM;The organization seeks volunteers and donations.andP;  Write them at ProjectNotify, Box 8656, Incline Village, Nevada 89450 or call 702-831-2011.andM;(Wendy Woods/19891124)</TEXT></DOC>